a contest. In the mid-1940s, [[Joe Weider|Joe]] and [[Ben Weider]] started the [[International Federation of BodyBuilders|IFBB]] as an alternative to the AAU.  They held their opposing contest, the IFBB Mr. America, in 1949 and then from 1959 through 1977.<ref name=mrahistory>{{cite web |url=http://mramerica.com/history/ |website=mramerica.com |title=Mr. America History |access-date=May 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614175104/http://mramerica.com/history/ |archive-date=June 14, 2017 }}</ref> Rights to the Mr. America name have been sold several times after AAU discontinued holding the contests in 1999.\n\n==History==\nThe AAU voted to discontinue holding bodybuilding competitions in 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In March 2017, AAU Strength Sports Chairman Martin Drake brought bodybuilding and fitness back to the AAU.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://aaustrengthsports.org/news.php?news_id=1661625 |title=2018 AAU Strength Sports Recognition Program |website=AAU Strength Sports |date=May 7, 2018 |publisher=Amateur Athletic Union |access-date=April 9, 2020 |quote=2017 [...] with the return of AAU Bodybuilding }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the World Bodybuilding & Fitness Association (WBFA) announced they had acquired the rights to the Mr. America name and would resume running contests under that banner.\n\nBob Bonham acquired the rights and from 2011 through 2013 held the Mr America contest under the sanction of the INBF (International Natural Bodybuilding Federation), which is the amateur division of the WNBF (World Natural Bodybuilding Federation). The contests were drug tested under strict WADA (World Anti Doping Agency) guidelines using U.S. Olympic laboratory testing.\n\nIn 2015, rights to Mr. America were acquired by Bruce Ebel, and the contest's annual event cycle resumed via MRA Promotions.  Qualifying events in spring were sponsored by the [[National Gym Association]] (NGA), Nspire Sports League (NSL), and Ultimate Fitness Events (UFE).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mramerica.com/qualifying-events/ |title=Mr. America Qualifying Events |publisher=MRA Promotions |access-date=May 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030225736/http://mramerica.com/qualifying-events |archive-date=October 30, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Mr. America Expo and contest was to have been held in [[Baltimore]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mramerica.com/mr-america-info-registration/ |title=Mr. America Info and Registration |website=mramerica.com |access-date=May 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602093059/http://mramerica.com/mr-america-info-registration/ |archive-date=June 2, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the contest will resume as a non-sanctioned event (with no specific organization affiliation) promoted by Marc Tauriello of East Coast Fitness Concepts. The Mr. America Sports Festival & Expo will be held October 9\u201311, 2020, in Atlantic City, New Jersey.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Historic winners ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Overall Winner (AAU)<ref name=mrahistory /> !! Overall Winner (IFBB)<ref name=mrahistory />\n!Overall Winner (INBF)<ref name=jdfair>{{Cite book|last=Fair|first=John D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZeCEBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA372&lpg=PA372&dq=john+heart+mr+america+fair&source=bl&ots=RIr3tSK3bx&sig=ACfU3U1kgMzA_Hy3mCH-iuOTPpxOKHSr6A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjt4ubWiIzoAhXItp4KHYoJBXAQ6AEwF3oECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=john%20heart%20mr%20america%20fair&f=false|title=Mr. America: The Tragic History of a Bodybuilding Icon|date=2015-01-05|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-76082-0|language=en}}</ref>\n!Overall Winner (Unsanctioned)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1939 || Bert Goodrich (First Mr. America, but not AAU sanctioned)<ref>{{cite book |first=John D. |last=Fair |title=Mr. America |at=Appendix |isbn=978-0292760820 |year=2015 |publisher=University of Texas }}</ref>\n|&nbsp;\n|\n|\n|-\n| [[Rol