{"title_page": "The Wild Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name = The Wild Center\n| logo = Wild center logo.png\n| image = Wild center main building.jpg\n| caption = The Wild Center viewed from Rainbow Bridge\n| alt = Exterior of main museum building viewed from Rainbow Bridge\n| map_type = \n| coordinates = {{coord|44.219709|-74.438543|display=inline}}\n| former_name = Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks\n| established = {{Start date|2006}}\n| location = [[Tupper Lake, New York]]\n| type = [[Science museum]]\n| visitors = \n| director = Stephanie Ratcliffe\n| website = {{URL|http://www.wildcenter.org/|www.wildcenter.org}}\n}}\n[[Image:OTTERbluex.png|right|thumb|The center's previous logo]]\n[[Image:NHMOTA.JPG|thumb|Sign at main entrance to museum campus]]\n'''The Wild Center''', formerly known as the '''Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks''',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wildcenter.org/about-us/the-history-of-the-wild-center/|title=The History of The Wild Center|date=2013-06-15|work=Wild Center|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en}}</ref> is a [[natural history]] center in [[Tupper Lake, New York]], near the center of [[New York (state)|New York]] state's [[Adirondack Park]].\n\n==Exhibits==\nThe center mixes up the indoors and outdoors on a trail-filled {{convert|115|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus. The center opened Wild Walk in 2015, a thousand feet of bridges and platforms that rise up and eventually over the forest on the center's campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-trb-new-york-wild-center-20150408-story.html |title=Wild Walk coming to nature museum in New York's Adirondack Park - LA Times |newspaper=Latimes.com |date=April 9, 2015 |author=Mary Forgione |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> In addition to the outdoor experiences there are five primary indoor exhibit areas, The Pataki Hall of the Adirondacks contains The Living River Trail that circles the hall with live animal exhibits and a waterfall with the center's live otters.<ref name=landi2009>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124449834655195657 |title=The Wild Center Celebrates Adirondack Park's Natural Wonders and History |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=June 9, 2009 |author=Ann Landi |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> There are approximately 50 species of live animals at the center, many of them in habitats in this hall. The Big Wolf Great Hall contains a [[lean-to]] and the glacial ice wall and is the site for the center's live animal encounters.<ref name=landi2009 /> The Naturalist Cabinet contains hands-on exhibits and collections. Other exhibit areas include the Flammer Panoramas Theater where films are screened, and Planet Adirondacks, an installation of the [[NOAA]]'s [[Science on a Sphere]]  with shows focusing on the relationship between the Adirondacks and the rest of the Earth. The center features live exhibits and live animals, including [[North American river otter|river otter]]s, birds, amphibians and fish. Indoors, a marsh appears to flow into a real pond that laps at the outside of the building, and the calls of live owls and otters mix with the splashing cascade of a trout-filled indoor stream. High definition films in a wide-screen theater explore the region and showcase fascinating reports from field scientists researching everything from moose to loons to alpine summits.\n\nThe center also includes outdoor exhibits that take visitors into the ecosystems that surround the center. There are canoe trips available on the river that runs through its campus. Daily guided trail walks are also offered. The walks are on provided snow shoes in the winter.\n\n==Awards==\nThe center was named a 2015 finalist for the [[National Medal for Museum and Library Service|National Medal]], the nation's highest honor for museums in service of their communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imls.gov/news-events/news-releases/thirty-museums-and-libraries-tapped-finalists-national-medal |title=Thirty Museums and Libraries Tapped as Finalists for National Medal |website=www.imls.gov |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}</ref> This center is the first [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] museum in New York. It earned a silver LEED award from the [[U.S. Green Building Council]]. The center has an extensive exhibit that details the LEED aspects of its facility.<ref name=landi2009 />\n\n==Programs==\nThe center plays a role in a range of Adirondack projects, sponsoring a community maple sugar operation, sponsoring an annual youth summit that brings college and high school students together to research climate impacts and develop campus action plans. It has partnered in this effort with the Association of Science and Technology Centers (ASTC), and [[Heureka (science center)|Heureka]] Science Center in Finland.\n\n==Design==\nThe building and the exhibits were designed by The Office of Charles P. Reay with Fish Partners and the [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] architectural firm [[Hellmuth, Obata and Kassabaum|HOK]].  The Bio Building was designed by local architecture firm Phinney Design Group,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phinneydesign.com/project/the-bio-building-at-the-natural-history-museum-of-the-adirondacks-commerical/ |title=The Bio Building at The Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks |website=Phinneydesign.com |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}</ref> based in [[Saratoga Springs]]. It opened on July 4, 2006.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Adirondack Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.wildcenter.org/ |title=Wild Center |website=Wildcenter.org |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0901/p11s02-algn.html |title=Inside this museum, the great outdoors |newspaper=Csmonitor.com |date=September 1, 2006 |author=Clayton Collins |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Natural history museums in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Museums in Franklin County, New York]]\n[[Category:Adirondacks]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Adirondack Park]]\n[[Category:Nature centers in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name = The Wild Center\n| logo = Wild center logo.png\n| image = Wild center main building.jpg\n| caption = The Wild Center viewed from Rainbow Bridge\n| alt = Exterior of main museum building viewed from Rainbow Bridge\n| map_type = \n| coordinates = {{coord|44.219709|-74.438543|display=inline}}\n| former_name = Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks\n| established = {{Start date|2006}}\n| location = [[Tupper Lake, New York]]\n| type = [[Science museum]]\n| visitors = \n| director = Stephanie Ratcliffe\n| website = {{URL|http://www.wildcenter.org/|www.wildcenter.org}}\n}}\n[[Image:OTTERbluex.png|right|thumb|The center's previous logo]]\n[[Image:NHMOTA.JPG|thumb|Sign at main entrance to museum campus]]\n'''The Wild Center''', formerly known as the '''Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks''',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wildcenter.org/about-us/the-history-of-the-wild-center/|title=The History of The Wild Center|date=2013-06-15|work=Wild Center|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en}}</ref> is a [[natural history]] center in [[Tupper Lake, New York]], near the center of [[New York (state)|New York]] state's [[Adirondack Park]].\n\n==Exhibits==\nThe center mixes up the indoors and outdoors on a trail-filled {{convert|115|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus. The center opened Wild Walk in 2015, a thousand feet of bridges and platforms that rise up and eventually over the forest on the center's campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-trb-new-york-wild-center-20150408-story.html |title=Wild Walk coming to nature museum in New York's Adirondack Park - LA Times |newspaper=Latimes.com |date=April 9, 2015 |author=Mary Forgione |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> In addition to the outdoor experiences there are five primary indoor exhibit areas, The Pataki Hall of the Adirondacks contains The Living River Trail that circles the hall with live animal exhibits and a waterfall with the center's live otters.<ref name=landi2009>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124449834655195657 |title=The Wild Center Celebrates Adirondack Park's Natural Wonders and History |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=June 9, 2009 |author=Ann Landi |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> There are approximately 50 species of live animals at the center, many of them in habitats in this hall. The Big Wolf Great Hall contains a [[lean-to]] and the glacial ice wall and is the site for the center's live animal encounters.<ref name=landi2009 /> The Naturalist Cabinet contains hands-on exhibits and collections. Other exhibit areas include the Flammer Panoramas Theater where films are screened, and Planet Adirondacks, an installation of the [[NOAA]]'s [[Science on a Sphere]]  with shows focusing on the relationship between the Adirondacks and the rest of the Earth. The center features live exhibits and live animals, including [[North American river otter|river otter]]s, birds, amphibians and fish. Indoors, a marsh appears to flow into a real pond that laps at the outside of the building, and the calls of live owls and otters mix with the splashing cascade of a trout-filled indoor stream. High definition films in a wide-screen theater explore the region and showcase fascinating reports from field scientists researching everything from moose to loons to alpine summits.\n\nThe center also includes outdoor exhibits that take visitors into the ecosystems that surround the center. There are canoe trips available on the river that runs though its campus. Daily guided trail walks are also offered. The walks are on provided snow shoes in the winter.\n\n==Awards==\nThe center was named a 2015 finalist for the [[National Medal for Museum and Library Service|National Medal]], the nation's highest honor for museums in service of their communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imls.gov/news-events/news-releases/thirty-museums-and-libraries-tapped-finalists-national-medal |title=Thirty Museums and Libraries Tapped as Finalists for National Medal |website=www.imls.gov |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}</ref> This center is the first [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] museum in New York. It earned a silver LEED award from the [[U.S. Green Building Council]]. The center has an extensive exhibit that details the LEED aspects of its facility.<ref name=landi2009 />\n\n==Programs==\nThe center plays a role in a range of Adirondack projects, sponsoring a community maple sugar operation, sponsoring an annual youth summit that brings college and high school students together to research climate impacts and develop campus action plans. It has partnered in this effort with the Association of Science and Technology Centers (ASTC), and [[Heureka (science center)|Heureka]] Science Center in Finland.\n\n==Design==\nThe building and the exhibits were designed by The Office of Charles P. Reay with Fish Partners and the [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] architectural firm [[Hellmuth, Obata and Kassabaum|HOK]].  The Bio Building was designed by local architecture firm Phinney Design Group,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phinneydesign.com/project/the-bio-building-at-the-natural-history-museum-of-the-adirondacks-commerical/ |title=The Bio Building at The Natural History Museum of the Adirondacks |website=Phinneydesign.com |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}</ref> based in [[Saratoga Springs]]. It opened on July 4, 2006.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Adirondack Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.wildcenter.org/ |title=Wild Center |website=Wildcenter.org |accessdate= October 23, 2016}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0901/p11s02-algn.html |title=Inside this museum, the great outdoors |newspaper=Csmonitor.com |date=September 1, 2006 |author=Clayton Collins |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Natural history museums in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Museums in Franklin County, New York]]\n[[Category:Adirondacks]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Adirondack Park]]\n[[Category:Nature centers in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExhibits:Typo fixing, replaced: runs though  \u2192  runs through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wild_Center"}
{"title_page": "Saviour Machine", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{for|the [[David Bowie]] song|Saviour Machine (song)}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Saviour Machine\n| background = group_or_band\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| origin = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre = [[Symphonic gothic metal]], [[neoclassical metal]], [[Christian metal]]\n| years_active = 1989\u20132012, 2017\u2013present\n| current_members = [[Eric Clayton]]<br/>Jeff Clayton<br/>Charles Cooper<br/>Nathan Van Hala\n| past_members = Chris Fee<br/>Dean Forsyth<br/>Jayson Heart<br/>Victor Deaton<br/>[[Carl Johan Grimmark]]<br/>Thomas Weinesj\u00f6<br/>Samuel West\n}}\n\n'''Saviour Machine''' is an American gothic [[Christian metal]] band that formed in 1989. They have released five studio albums and two live albums on Frontline and subsequently on MCM Music, distributed through [[Massacre Records]]. Saviour Machine's music and lyrics deal with war, death, and personal introspection as it relates to prophecy and divine revelation.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ankeny, Jason |title= Saviour Machine |publisher=Open Publishing |date=February 4, 2004 |work=[[Allmusic]] |url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p296142|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and early years (1989\u20131993)===\nThe band was formed by brothers Jeff and [[Eric Clayton]] in mid-1989. By the time of its first tour in 1993, the band was Eric Clayton \u2013 vocals, Jeff Clayton \u2013 guitars, Dean Forsyth \u2013 bass, Jayson Heart \u2013 drums, and Nathan Van Hala \u2013 keyboards. The band took its name from a song on the [[David Bowie]] album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]''. Saviour Machine recorded and released their first demos in 1990. A theatrical stage show featuring [[pyrotechnics]], images projected onto a background screen and other [[theatrical properties|props]] attracted a growing fan base in [[Southern California]].  \n{{Listen\n|filename=Saviour Machine - Legion.ogg\n|title=\"Legion\"\n|description=Sample of \"Legion\" by Saviour Machine, from ''[[Saviour Machine I]]'' (1993).  Containing lyrics with apocalyptic themes, this song eventually led to the album being banned from Christian bookstores in the United States.}}\n\nIn 1993, with the help of Deliverance frontman Jimmy P. Brown II, Saviour Machine signed with and released their first full-length album on Intense Records, an imprint of the Frontline subsidiary of [[Roadrunner Records]]. Musically, the band developed a guitar-driven rock music sound, featuring melodic [[riff]]s and extensive solos by Jeff Clayton.\n\nDespite critical acclaim from the mainstream press<ref>{{cite web |author=Espiau, Olivier |title=Saviour Machine - Saviour Machine II |publisher=Open Publishing |year=2004 |work=Metal Storm |url= http://www.metalstorm.ee/pub/review.php?review_id=292&print_page=yes |accessdate=September 9, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Espiau, Olivier |title= Saviour Machine - Saviour Machine I |publisher=Open Publishing |date=February 4, 2004 |work=Metal Storm |url= http://www.metalstorm.ee/bands/album.php?album_id=1033&band_id=149&bandname=Saviour+Machine |accessdate=September 9, 2007 }}</ref> and a growing number of fans nationwide, people in some conservative circles reportedly felt threatened by Saviour Machine's lyrical direction and stage presentation, most prominently the white make-up and jewel worn by vocalist Eric Clayton. During their 1993 tour with [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band [[Deliverance (metal band)|Deliverance]], the controversy spilled over at a concert at the New Union, a club in [[Minneapolis]]. Several songs into their set, the power was cut and the performers were ushered from the stage. This was followed by an announcement from New Union management stating they were uncomfortable with the content of the show. However, many in the crowd gathered with the band shortly after at a local [[White Castle (restaurant)|White Castle]] restaurant to show their continued support.{{ref|1}}\n\n===Studio transition (1994\u20131996)===\nConfusion and political upheaval at Intense/Frontline led to less-than-ideal conditions for the recording of the band's next album in 1994, ''Saviour Machine II''. Musically, the addition of [[pianist]] Nathan Van Hala resulted in a [[european classical music|classical music]]-based sound.  Many songs featured [[piano]] compositions and [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] [[orchestration]]. Charles Cooper also joined the band at this time after Dean Forsyth left.\n\nWith the release of ''Saviour Machine II'' the band began to pursue new representation. A growing following had developed in [[Europe]], particularly in [[Germany]]. This led to the formation of MCM Music, an independent label for all Saviour Machine projects, by vocalist Eric Clayton and his European management team. The band also secured a deal with [[Massacre Records]], a German label that specializes in death metal and other heavy/extreme music. Saviour Machine was given full creative control on all future projects.\n\nMultiple tours of [[Europe]] followed in 1995 and 1996. During a 1995 performance at Owen Teck Rocknight, a [[music festival]] in Owen, [[Germany]], Saviour Machine recorded their first live album. ''Live in Deutschland'', released in 1995, featured selections from ''Saviour Machine I'' and ''Saviour Machine II''. It was after this tour that the membership of Saviour Machine changed with the replacement of Jeff Clayton by Joshua. They performed at [[Wacken Open Air]] festival in 1997.\n\n===The ''Legend'' trilogy (1997\u20132007)===\nSaviour Machine next turned to the ''Legend'' trilogy. ''Legend'' was advertised as \"the unofficial soundtrack to the end of the world\" in promotional materials<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> owing to its study of [[end times|end-time]] [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecy]]. The ''Legend'' trilogy comprises four full-length CDs totaling more than five hours of music. ''Legend I'' and ''Legend II'' were released in 1997 and 1998, respectively. The studio composition of the band stayed the same through \"Legend II\" after which Jeff Clayton and Jayson Heart left the band. ''[[Legend III:I]]'' was released in 2001. The long-awaited final disc, ''Legend III:II'', was scheduled to be released July 7, 2007. ''Legend'' parts ''I'' through ''III:I'' were released by MCM Music and Massacre Records; however, ''Legend III:II'' was released independently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 |title=Eric Clayton im Interview |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |author=Brunner, David |date=August 11, 2006 |work=Sound7.de |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223232552/http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 |archivedate=December 23, 2007 }}</ref> On May 27, 2007, Eric Clayton released a statement on the Saviour Machine MySpace blog saying that, due to health problems, he would not be able to finish ''Legend III:II'' in time to make the July 7 release date. He released samples of rough mixes of each song on ''Legend III:II'' on SeventhCircle.net throughout July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seventhcircle.net/legend.htm |title=''Legend Part III:II'' |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |author=Clayton, Eric |date=July 7, 2007 |work=Sound7.de |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209071516/http://www.seventhcircle.net/legend.htm |archivedate=December 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMost of the lyrical content of the ''Legend'' series is based on the [[Book of Revelation]] and other [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecy]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> The first album draws from the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]], except the [[Book of Revelation]], and include biblical references and a [[Concordance (publishing)|concordance]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\">{{cite journal |last=Macintosh |first=Dan |date=May\u2013June 1997 |title=Saviour Machine |journal=[[HM Magazine]] |issn=1066-6923 |issue=65 |url=http://www.hmmagazine.com/archives/Saviour+Machine.htm |accessdate=April 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918053800/http://www.hmmagazine.com/archives/Saviour%20Machine.htm |archivedate=September 18, 2000 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Legend II'' continues where part one ended - the rise of the [[antichrist]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> Musically, the ''Legend'' albums showcase a further refinement of Saviour Machine's [[Rock music|rock]] and [[classical music]] style.\n\nSaviour Machine has performed a limited number of concerts in the US, Germany and [[Mexico City]] since undertaking the ''Legend'' trilogy. A second live album was released in 2002, again featuring a performance from Owen Teck Rocknight in Owen, Germany. ''Live in Deutschland 2002'' featured selections from ''Legend I'', ''Legend II'' and ''Legend III:I''.\n\n===Inactive years (2008\u20132016)===\nEric Clayton has repeatedly stated that Saviour Machine's work will end upon the completion of the ''Legend'' trilogy. In a video message created on September 3, 2009, Eric stated that despite his frail health he is doing quite well and plans to release segments from a journal he has been keeping since 1997. He said that the excerpts will likely serve as his final interview.<ref>[http://www.saviourmachine.com Saviour Machine Home Page - A Message From Eric Clayton]</ref>\n\nDespite these statements, Saviour Machine's homepage went offline in 2013.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}} Saviour Machine's Facebook page, which had received regular updates through 2012, also went inactive during 2013, and subsequently was taken down in 2014.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}} Eric Clayton officially retired Saviour Machine as a band and the whole unfinished Legend project in the same year.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n=== Re-union and plan for new release (2017\u2013present) ===\n\nAccording to an interview with Eric Clayton during [[Wacken Open Air]] 2017 as well as statements on the Facebook page and Youtube channel of the band, they are working on a new album to be released in the future. It will not be part of the Legend-trilogy, but follow the first two releases of the band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLG-rndfRYVoapziCMqUe2onQIof2JaurK|title=Eric Clayton - Wacken Press Conference 2017 - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Year\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Title\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Label\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Other information\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1990\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Saviour Machine (demo)'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Independent\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music in 1997\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1993\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''[[Saviour Machine I]]'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Intense Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music / Massacre Records in 1996\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1994\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Saviour Machine II'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Intense Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music / Massacre Records in 1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1995\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Live in Deutschland 1995'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|CD and VHS\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1997\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend I'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Review: [http://www.tollbooth.org/reviews/sm.html The Phantom Tollbooth]\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1998\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend II'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Reviews: [http://www.tollbooth.org/reviews/sm2.html The Phantom Tollbooth], [https://web.archive.org/web/20010713013634/http://www.hmmagazine.com/issue72/72Albums.htm HM Magazine]<ref name=\"HM_72\">{{cite journal |last=Van Pelt |first=Doug |date=July\u2013August 1998 |title=Album Reviews: SAVIOUR MACHINE ''Legend Part II'' |journal=[[HM Magazine]] |issn=1066-6923 |issue=72 |pages= }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2001\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend III:I'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Exclusive first pressing; Limited to 2001 hand-numbered copies\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2002\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Live in Deutschland 2002'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2CD and 2DVD; DVD includes re-release of ''Live in Deutschland 1995''\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2006\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Rarities / Revelations'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Independent\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|4CD; Limited to 500 hand-numbered copies signed by Eric Clayton\n|-\n|}\n\n==Members==\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Eric Clayton]] \u2013 vocals <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Jeff Clayton \u2013 guitar <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Nathan Van Hala \u2013 piano <small>(1993\u2013present)</small>\n* Charles Cooper \u2013 bass <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>\n*Samuel West \u2013 drums <small>(1992\u20131993, 2011\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Chris Fee \u2013 drums <small>(1989\u20131992)</small>{{Citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n* Dean Forsyth \u2013 bass <small>(1989\u20131995)</small>\n* Jayson Heart \u2013 drums <small>(1993\u20131999)</small>\n* Victor Deaton \u2013 drums <small>(2000\u20132001)</small>\n* [[Carl Johan Grimmark]] \u2013 guitar <small>(2001\u20132004)</small>\n* Thomas Weinesj\u00f6 \u2013 drums <small>(2001\u20132004)</small>\n\n==Side projects==\n*Eric Clayton appeared as \"Reason\" on [[Ayreon|Ayreon's]] 2004 album, ''[[The Human Equation]]'', which also featured [[James LaBrie]], [[Mikael \u00c5kerfeldt]] and [[Devin Townsend]], among others. He reprised this role in the 2015 theater adaptation of this album.\n* In 1998, he produced and performed guest vocals on Wedding Party's album, ''Anthems''. Clayton also produced and performed guest vocals in [[Eva O]]'s album, ''Damnation: Ride the Madness''.\n*Carl Johan Grimmark is the lead guitarist for [[Narnia (band)|Narnia]] and also performs with [[Rob Rock]].\n*Nathan Van Hala currently plays keyboards for The Fur Traders. Past projects include [[Eagle Winged Palace]], [[West Indian Girl]], X-electra, [[Shadow Project]], and Strychnine Kiss, for whom he was the vocalist and primary songwriter.\n*Thomas Weinesj\u00f6 is the drummer for [[Veni Domine]].\n*Former drummer Victor Deaton played drums on two tracks (\"Raven's Warning\" and \"Alliance\") and marching snare drum (percussion) on one track (\"War Memorial\") of Wedding Party's record ''Anthems''. It is also rumored that Victor Deaton played drums on the ''Rackets and Drapes'' album \"Trick or Treat\". Hence, the liner notes of the album contained, \"BAND THANX: ...,Vic Deaton for the music lessons,...\" Victor Deaton has also recorded with guitarist [[Phil Keaggy]].\n*Former drummer Sam West is currently a member of [[Stavesacre]], and previously performed with [[Scaterd Few]] and [[The Violet Burning]].\n*Eric Clayton guested Carl Johan Grimmarks headproject [[Narnia (Swedish band)|Narnia]] on the album ''The Great Fall'' and sang the vocals with Christian Rivel on the 14 minute song ''The Great Fall of Man''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{note|Deus Ex Machina}} {{cite web | title = 1 | work = Deus Ex Machina | url= http://www.wp.cc.nc.us/~rbuff/ectalks.html | accessdate=March 1, 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/19971025044139/http://www.wp.cc.nc.us/~rbuff/ectalks.html | archivedate = October 25, 1997}}\n*{{note|Sound7}} {{cite web | title = 2 | work = Deus Ex Machina | url= http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 | accessdate=March 13, 2007}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/saviourmachineband/ Official Facebook Page]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCX2-AldkSHJJ7eoX95CLwZQ Official Youtube Channel]\n* [https://saviourmachine.bandcamp.com/ Official Bandcamp Page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131204175713/http://www.saviourmachine.com/ Old website on WebArchive.org]\n\n{{Saviour Machine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American symphonic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:American gothic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{for|the [[David Bowie]] song|Saviour Machine (song)}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Saviour Machine\n| background = group_or_band\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| origin = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre = [[Symphonic gothic metal]], [[neoclassical metal]], [[Christian metal]]\n| years_active = 1989\u20132012, 2017\u2013present\n| current_members = [[Eric Clayton]]<br/>Jeff Clayton<br/>Charles Cooper<br/>Nathan Van Hala\n| past_members = Chris Fee<br/>Dean Forsyth<br/>Jayson Heart<br/>Victor Deaton<br/>[[Carl Johan Grimmark]]<br/>Thomas Weinesj\u00f6<br/>Samuel West\n}}\n\n'''Saviour Machine''' is an American gothic [[Christian metal]] band that formed in 1989. They have released five studio albums and two live albums on Frontline and subsequently on MCM Music, distributed through [[Massacre Records]]. Saviour Machine's music and lyrics deal with war, death, and personal introspection as it relates to prophecy and divine revelation.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ankeny, Jason |title= Saviour Machine |publisher=Open Publishing |date=February 4, 2004 |work=[[Allmusic]] |url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p296142|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and early years (1989 - 1993)===\nThe band was formed by brothers Jeff and [[Eric Clayton]] in mid-1989. By the time of its first tour in 1993, the band was Eric Clayton - vocals, Jeff Clayton - guitars, Dean Forsyth - bass, Jayson Heart - drums, and Nathan Van Hala - keyboards. The band took its name from a song on the [[David Bowie]] album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]''. Saviour Machine recorded and released their first demos in 1990. A theatrical stage show featuring [[pyrotechnics]], images projected onto a background screen and other [[theatrical properties|props]] attracted a growing fan base in [[Southern California]].  \n{{Listen\n|filename=Saviour Machine - Legion.ogg\n|title=\"Legion\"\n|description=Sample of \"Legion\" by Saviour Machine, from ''[[Saviour Machine I]]'' (1993).  Containing lyrics with apocalyptic themes, this song eventually led to the album being banned from Christian bookstores in the United States.}}\n\nIn 1993, with the help of Deliverance frontman Jimmy P. Brown II, Saviour Machine signed with and released their first full-length album on Intense Records, an imprint of the Frontline subsidiary of [[Roadrunner Records]]. Musically, the band developed a guitar-driven rock music sound, featuring melodic [[riff]]s and extensive solos by Jeff Clayton.\n\nDespite critical acclaim from the mainstream press<ref>{{cite web |author=Espiau, Olivier |title=Saviour Machine - Saviour Machine II |publisher=Open Publishing |year=2004 |work=Metal Storm |url= http://www.metalstorm.ee/pub/review.php?review_id=292&print_page=yes |accessdate=September 9, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Espiau, Olivier |title= Saviour Machine - Saviour Machine I |publisher=Open Publishing |date=February 4, 2004 |work=Metal Storm |url= http://www.metalstorm.ee/bands/album.php?album_id=1033&band_id=149&bandname=Saviour+Machine |accessdate=September 9, 2007 }}</ref> and a growing number of fans nationwide, people in some conservative circles reportedly felt threatened by Saviour Machine's lyrical direction and stage presentation, most prominently the white make-up and jewel worn by vocalist Eric Clayton. During their 1993 tour with [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band [[Deliverance (metal band)|Deliverance]], the controversy spilled over at a concert at the New Union, a club in [[Minneapolis]]. Several songs into their set, the power was cut and the performers were ushered from the stage. This was followed by an announcement from New Union management stating they were uncomfortable with the content of the show. However, many in the crowd gathered with the band shortly after at a local [[White Castle (restaurant)|White Castle]] restaurant to show their continued support.{{ref|1}}\n\n===Studio transition (1994 - 1996)===\nConfusion and political upheaval at Intense/Frontline led to less-than-ideal conditions for the recording of the band's next album in 1994, ''Saviour Machine II''. Musically, the addition of [[pianist]] Nathan Van Hala resulted in a [[european classical music|classical music]]-based sound.  Many songs featured [[piano]] compositions and [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] [[orchestration]]. Charles Cooper also joined the band at this time after Dean Forsyth left.\n\nWith the release of ''Saviour Machine II'' the band began to pursue new representation. A growing following had developed in [[Europe]], particularly in [[Germany]]. This led to the formation of MCM Music, an independent label for all Saviour Machine projects, by vocalist Eric Clayton and his European management team. The band also secured a deal with [[Massacre Records]], a German label that specializes in death metal and other heavy/extreme music. Saviour Machine was given full creative control on all future projects.\n\nMultiple tours of [[Europe]] followed in 1995 and 1996. During a 1995 performance at Owen Teck Rocknight, a [[music festival]] in Owen, [[Germany]], Saviour Machine recorded their first live album. ''Live in Deutschland'', released in 1995, featured selections from ''Saviour Machine I'' and ''Saviour Machine II''. It was after this tour that the membership of Saviour Machine changed with the replacement of Jeff Clayton by Joshua. They performed at [[Wacken Open Air]] festival in 1997.\n\n===The ''Legend'' trilogy (1997 - 2007)===\nSaviour Machine next turned to the ''Legend'' trilogy. ''Legend'' was advertised as \"the unofficial soundtrack to the end of the world\" in promotional materials<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> owing to its study of [[end times|end-time]] [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecy]]. The ''Legend'' trilogy comprises four full-length CDs totaling more than five hours of music. ''Legend I'' and ''Legend II'' were released in 1997 and 1998, respectively. The studio composition of the band stayed the same through \"Legend II\" after which Jeff Clayton and Jayson Heart left the band. ''[[Legend III:I]]'' was released in 2001. The long-awaited final disc, ''Legend III:II'', was scheduled to be released July 7, 2007. ''Legend'' parts ''I'' through ''III:I'' were released by MCM Music and Massacre Records; however, ''Legend III:II'' was released independently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 |title=Eric Clayton im Interview |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |author=Brunner, David |date=August 11, 2006 |work=Sound7.de |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223232552/http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 |archivedate=December 23, 2007 }}</ref> On May 27, 2007, Eric Clayton released a statement on the Saviour Machine MySpace blog saying that, due to health problems, he would not be able to finish ''Legend III:II'' in time to make the July 7 release date. He released samples of rough mixes of each song on ''Legend III:II'' on SeventhCircle.net throughout July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seventhcircle.net/legend.htm |title=''Legend Part III:II'' |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |author=Clayton, Eric |date=July 7, 2007 |work=Sound7.de |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209071516/http://www.seventhcircle.net/legend.htm |archivedate=December 9, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMost of the lyrical content of the ''Legend'' series is based on the [[Book of Revelation]] and other [[Bible prophecy|Biblical prophecy]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> The first album draws from the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]], except the [[Book of Revelation]], and include biblical references and a [[Concordance (publishing)|concordance]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\">{{cite journal |last=Macintosh |first=Dan |date=May\u2013June 1997 |title=Saviour Machine |journal=[[HM Magazine]] |issn=1066-6923 |issue=65 |url=http://www.hmmagazine.com/archives/Saviour+Machine.htm |accessdate=April 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918053800/http://www.hmmagazine.com/archives/Saviour%20Machine.htm |archivedate=September 18, 2000 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Legend II'' continues where part one ended - the rise of the [[antichrist]].<ref name=\"HM_97_65\"/> Musically, the ''Legend'' albums showcase a further refinement of Saviour Machine's [[Rock music|rock]] and [[classical music]] style.\n\nSaviour Machine has performed a limited number of concerts in the US, Germany and [[Mexico City]] since undertaking the ''Legend'' trilogy. A second live album was released in 2002, again featuring a performance from Owen Teck Rocknight in Owen, Germany. ''Live in Deutschland 2002'' featured selections from ''Legend I'', ''Legend II'' and ''Legend III:I''.\n\n===Inactive years (2008\u20132016)===\nEric Clayton has repeatedly stated that Saviour Machine's work will end upon the completion of the ''Legend'' trilogy. In a video message created on September 3, 2009, Eric stated that despite his frail health he is doing quite well and plans to release segments from a journal he has been keeping since 1997. He said that the excerpts will likely serve as his final interview.<ref>[http://www.saviourmachine.com Saviour Machine Home Page - A Message From Eric Clayton]</ref>\n\nDespite these statements, Saviour Machine's homepage went offline in 2013.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}} Saviour Machine's Facebook page, which had received regular updates through 2012, also went inactive during 2013, and subsequently was taken down in 2014.{{Citation needed|date=November 2014}} Eric Clayton officially retired Saviour Machine as a band and the whole unfinished Legend project in the same year.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n=== Re-union and plan for new release (2017\u2013present) ===\n\nAccording to an interview with Eric Clayton during [[Wacken Open Air]] 2017 as well as statements on the Facebook page and Youtube channel of the band, they are working on a new album to be released in the future. It will not be part of the Legend-trilogy, but follow the first two releases of the band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLG-rndfRYVoapziCMqUe2onQIof2JaurK|title=Eric Clayton - Wacken Press Conference 2017 - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Year\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Title\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Label\n!align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Other information\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1990\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Saviour Machine (demo)'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Independent\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music in 1997\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1993\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''[[Saviour Machine I]]'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Intense Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music / Massacre Records in 1996\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1994\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Saviour Machine II'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Intense Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Re-released on MCM Music / Massacre Records in 1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1995\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Live in Deutschland 1995'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|CD and VHS\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1997\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend I'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Review: [http://www.tollbooth.org/reviews/sm.html The Phantom Tollbooth]\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|1998\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend II'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Reviews: [http://www.tollbooth.org/reviews/sm2.html The Phantom Tollbooth], [https://web.archive.org/web/20010713013634/http://www.hmmagazine.com/issue72/72Albums.htm HM Magazine]<ref name=\"HM_72\">{{cite journal |last=Van Pelt |first=Doug |date=July\u2013August 1998 |title=Album Reviews: SAVIOUR MACHINE ''Legend Part II'' |journal=[[HM Magazine]] |issn=1066-6923 |issue=72 |pages= }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2001\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Legend III:I'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Exclusive first pressing; Limited to 2001 hand-numbered copies\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2002\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Live in Deutschland 2002'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|MCM Music / Massacre Records\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2CD and 2DVD; DVD includes re-release of ''Live in Deutschland 1995''\n|-\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|2006\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|''Rarities / Revelations'' \n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|Independent\n|align=\"left\" valign=\"top\"|4CD; Limited to 500 hand-numbered copies signed by Eric Clayton\n|-\n|}\n\n==Members==\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Eric Clayton]] \u2013 vocals <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Jeff Clayton \u2013 guitar <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Nathan Van Hala \u2013 piano <small>(1993\u2013present)</small>\n* Charles Cooper \u2013 bass <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>\n*Samuel West \u2013 drums <small>(1992\u20131993, 2011\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Chris Fee \u2013 drums <small>(1989\u20131992)</small>{{Citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n* Dean Forsyth \u2013 bass <small>(1989\u20131995)</small>\n* Jayson Heart \u2013 drums <small>(1993\u20131999)</small>\n* Victor Deaton \u2013 drums <small>(2000\u20132001)</small>\n* [[Carl Johan Grimmark]] \u2013 guitar <small>(2001\u20132004)</small>\n* Thomas Weinesj\u00f6 \u2013 drums <small>(2001\u20132004)</small>\n\n==Side projects==\n*Eric Clayton appeared as \"Reason\" on [[Ayreon|Ayreon's]] 2004 album, ''[[The Human Equation]]'', which also featured [[James LaBrie]], [[Mikael \u00c5kerfeldt]] and [[Devin Townsend]], among others. He reprised this role in the 2015 theater adaptation of this album.\n* In 1998, he produced and performed guest vocals on Wedding Party's album, ''Anthems''. Clayton also produced and performed guest vocals in [[Eva O]]'s album, ''Damnation: Ride the Madness''.\n*Carl Johan Grimmark is the lead guitarist for [[Narnia (band)|Narnia]] and also performs with [[Rob Rock]].\n*Nathan Van Hala currently plays keyboards for The Fur Traders. Past projects include [[Eagle Winged Palace]], [[West Indian Girl]], X-electra, [[Shadow Project]], and Strychnine Kiss, for whom he was the vocalist and primary songwriter.\n*Thomas Weinesj\u00f6 is the drummer for [[Veni Domine]].\n*Former drummer Victor Deaton played drums on two tracks (\"Raven's Warning\" and \"Alliance\") and marching snare drum (percussion) on one track (\"War Memorial\") of Wedding Party's record ''Anthems''. It is also rumored that Victor Deaton played drums on the ''Rackets and Drapes'' album \"Trick or Treat\". Hence, the liner notes of the album contained, \"BAND THANX: ...,Vic Deaton for the music lessons,...\" Victor Deaton has also recorded with guitarist [[Phil Keaggy]].\n*Former drummer Sam West is currently a member of [[Stavesacre]], and previously performed with [[Scaterd Few]] and [[The Violet Burning]].\n*Eric Clayton guested Carl Johan Grimmarks headproject [[Narnia (Swedish band)|Narnia]] on the album ''The Great Fall'' and sang the vocals with Christian Rivel on the 14 minute song ''The Great Fall of Man''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{note|Deus Ex Machina}} {{cite web | title = 1 | work = Deus Ex Machina | url= http://www.wp.cc.nc.us/~rbuff/ectalks.html | accessdate=March 1, 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/19971025044139/http://www.wp.cc.nc.us/~rbuff/ectalks.html | archivedate = October 25, 1997}}\n*{{note|Sound7}} {{cite web | title = 2 | work = Deus Ex Machina | url= http://www.sound7.de/article.php?channel=3&article=4154 | accessdate=March 13, 2007}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/saviourmachineband/ Official Facebook Page]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCX2-AldkSHJJ7eoX95CLwZQ Official Youtube Channel]\n* [https://saviourmachine.bandcamp.com/ Official Bandcamp Page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131204175713/http://www.saviourmachine.com/ Old website on WebArchive.org]\n\n{{Saviour Machine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American symphonic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:American gothic metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from California]]\n", "name_user": "Shrikesong", "label": "safe", "comment": "Some dash fixes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saviour_Machine"}
{"title_page": "Vasyl Chuchupak", "text_new": "[[image:\u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a-\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c-\u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Insurgent otaman Vasyl Chuchupak]]\n'''Vasyl Stepanovych Chuchupak''' ({{lang-uk|\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a}}) (11 March 1895 - 12 April 1920) was the leader of the [[Kholodny Yar]] Ukrainian [[Partisan (military)|partisan]] movement during the [[Ukrainian War of Independence]].<ref name=G121214>[http://gazeta.ua/articles/culture-newspaper/_rosijskoukrayinska-vijna-nikoli-ne-pripinyalasya/598335 \"Russian-Ukrainian war never stopped\"], [[Gazeta.ua]] (12 December 2014)</ref><ref name=Den22211>[http://day.kyiv.ua/en/article/culture/kholodny-yar-alive \u201cKholodny Yar is alive\u2026\u201d], [[The Day (Kiev)|Den]] (22 February 2011)</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:\u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a.jpg|thumb|Chuchupak's grave in the cemetery of Melnyky|200px|right]]\n\n\nBorn in 1895 in the village Melnyky in the [[Chyhyryn]] region, Chuchupak served in the [[Imperial Russian Army]] with his brother Petro and was a village teacher.<ref name=\"G121214\" /><ref name=\"VCUinfld\">{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.ukrinform.ua/rubric-society/2069551-ludi-svobodi-kalinovij-svit-bilokur-pisenna-dusa-ivasuka-gart-stusa-plomin-cornovola.html People freedom], [[Ukrinform]] (21 August 2016)</ref>\n\nChuchupak's family was highly regarded within the Melnyky village. They were a wealthy peasants and provided a good education for their offsprings. In particular, Vasyl's brothers Oleksa Chuchupak and Semen Chuchupak were a village teachers, and Petro Chuchupak studied in Kyiv Academy of Music, furhermore, some of his relatives were priests, namely, Demian and Avtonom Chuchupaks. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dsnews.ua/nasha_revolyutsiya_1917/-nevblaganniy-vorog-yak-povstala-respublika-holodnogo-19022020200000|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0432\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\". \u042f\u043a \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u042f\u0440\u0443|website=www.dsnews.ua|language=ru|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nChuchupak was the leader ([[Otaman]]<ref name=Den22211/>) of the [[Kholodny Yar]] Ukrainian [[Partisan (military)|partisan]] movement during the [[Ukrainian War of Independence]].<ref name=G121214/> In current [[Chyhyryn Raion]] this movement formed the [[Kholodny Yar Republic]] that lasted from 1919 to 1922 were they fought for Ukrainian independence and against the [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.ukrinform.ua/rubric-society/2104087-irina-gerasenko-proponue-stvoriti-nacionalnij-park-holodnij-ar.html Gerashchenko offers a National Park \"Cold Yar\"], [[Ukrinform]] (19 October 2016)</ref> The republic included 25 villages (with Melnyky serving as its \u201ccapital\u201d<ref name=Den22211/>) and could raise an army of 16 thousand.<ref name=KRbt20s/> It was the last territory held by supporters of an independent Ukrainian state before the incorporating of Ukraine into the Soviet Union as the [[Ukrainian SSR]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://gazeta.ua/articles/ukraine-newspaper/_na-vshanuvanni-otamana-osvyachuvali-nozhi/336125?mobile=true In honor of the chieftain blessed knives], [[Gazeta.ua]] (21 April 2010)</ref>\n\nThe teacher's repuation and his organizational skills with transferrable war experience skills made a creation of a strong insurgent organization as a segment of Ukrainian National Republic possible\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dsnews.ua/nasha_revolyutsiya_1917/-nevblaganniy-vorog-yak-povstala-respublika-holodnogo-19022020200000|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0432\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\". \u042f\u043a \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u042f\u0440\u0443|website=www.dsnews.ua|language=ru|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe best evaluation to Vasyl's Chuchupaka role of that period was given by White guards in the Autumn 1919: Chuchupaka is independence minded, he has a support amongst a village's intelligentsia and a peasants' segment. He demonstrates an ability to be rigorous in connection with stealing within the army and tries to create a disciplined army\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dsnews.ua/nasha_revolyutsiya_1917/-nevblaganniy-vorog-yak-povstala-respublika-holodnogo-19022020200000|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0432\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\". \u042f\u043a \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u042f\u0440\u0443|website=www.dsnews.ua|language=ru|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nChuchupak shot and killed himself on 12 April 1920 in fight with squadron of [[red cossacks]].<ref name=VCUinfld/><ref name=KRbt20s>{{in lang|uk}} [http://gazeta.ua/articles/cherkasy-newspaper/_na-mogilu-otamana-cuchupaki-priyihali-dvi-tisyachi-lyudej/289494 At the grave chieftain Chuchupaky came two thousand people], [[Gazeta.ua]] (16 April 2009)</ref>\n\nIn the [[21st century]] the Kholodny Republic flag was used during the [[Euromaidan]] demonstrations and by the [[Azov Battalion]].<ref name=G121214/> In January 2018 the [[93rd Mechanized Brigade (Ukraine)|93rd Mechanized Brigade]] of the [[Ukrainian army]] received the honorary name \"Kholodny Yar\" as reference to the Kholodny Yar partisan movement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukrmilitary.com/2018/01/honory-names-of-93rd-brigade.html |title=93-\u044f \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u0456\u043c'\u044f \u00ab\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u00bb |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=www.ukrmilitary.com/ |publisher=[[Ukrainian Military Pages]] |accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://procherk.info/news/7-cherkassy/59835-93-a-okrema-mehanizovana-brigada-zsu-otrimae-pochesne-najmenuvannja-holodnij-jar |title=93-\u0442\u044f \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u00ab\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u00bb |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=procherk.info/ |publisher=[[\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a (\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f)|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mil.in.ua/holodnyy-yar-pochesna-nazva-93-bryhady/ |title=\u201c\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u201d: \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430 93 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0438 |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=mil.in.ua |publisher=[[\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0456\u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tsn.ua/ukrayina/93-a-brigada-zsu-otrimaye-pochesne-naymenuvannya-holodniy-yar-novi-shevroni-ta-boyoviy-prapor-1092280.html?g=article&m=400342745 |title=93-\u0442\u044f \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \"\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\", \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0456 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043e |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=tsn.ua/ |publisher=[[\u0422\u0421\u041d]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://milnavigator.com.ua/93-\u043e\u043c\u0431\u0440-\u0437\u0441\u0443-\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435-\u0445\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e-\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e/ 93 \u041e\u041c\u0411\u0440 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e. \u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e] // ''[[\u0412\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0456\u0433\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-41973466 |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0456\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0456 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0430\u043a: \u044f\u043a \u0437\u043c\u0456\u043d\u044e\u044e\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |author= |date=2017-11-14 |website=www.bbc.com/ |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://novynarnia.com/2017/10/15/pochesni-styagi-poruch-z-boyovimi-sso-i-brigada-korolya-danila-otrimali-brendovu-simvoliku/ |title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0456 \u0441\u0442\u044f\u0433\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0447 \u0437 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c\u0438. \u0421\u0421\u041e \u0456 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044f \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u201c\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0443\u201d \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0443 |author= |date=2017-10-15 |website=novynarnia.com|publisher=[[\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043d\u044f]] |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.slavaukraini.org/index.php?id=5#c7 www.slavaukraini.org]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140808074851/http://ukrgazeta.plus.org.ua/article.php?ida=2219 \u0413\u0415\u0420\u041e\u0407 \u00ab\u0425\u041e\u041b\u041e\u0414\u041d\u041e\u042f\u0420\u0421\u042c\u041a\u041e\u0407 \u0414\u0415\u0420\u0416\u0410\u0412\u0418\u00bb] on ukrgazeta\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chuchupak, Vasyl Stepanovych}}\n\n{{ua-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1920 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chyhyryn Raion]]\n[[Category:People of the Russian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian guerrillas]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian military leaders]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian nationalists]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Russian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian military personnel]]\n", "text_old": "[[image:\u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a-\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c-\u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Insurgent otaman Vasyl Chuchupak]]\n'''Vasyl Stepanovych Chuchupak''' ({{lang-uk|\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a}}) (11 March 1895 - 12 April 1920) was the leader of the [[Kholodny Yar]] Ukrainian [[Partisan (military)|partisan]] movement during the [[Ukrainian War of Independence]].<ref name=G121214>[http://gazeta.ua/articles/culture-newspaper/_rosijskoukrayinska-vijna-nikoli-ne-pripinyalasya/598335 \"Russian-Ukrainian war never stopped\"], [[Gazeta.ua]] (12 December 2014)</ref><ref name=Den22211>[http://day.kyiv.ua/en/article/culture/kholodny-yar-alive \u201cKholodny Yar is alive\u2026\u201d], [[The Day (Kiev)|Den]] (22 February 2011)</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:\u0427\u0443\u0447\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043a.jpg|thumb|Chuchupak's grave in the cemetery of Melnyky|200px|right]]\n\nBorn in 1895 in the village Melnyky in the [[Chyhyryn]] region, Chuchupak served in the [[Imperial Russian Army]] and was a village teacher.<ref name=G121214/><ref name=VCUinfld>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.ukrinform.ua/rubric-society/2069551-ludi-svobodi-kalinovij-svit-bilokur-pisenna-dusa-ivasuka-gart-stusa-plomin-cornovola.html People freedom], [[Ukrinform]] (21 August 2016)</ref>\n\nChuchupak was the leader ([[Otaman]]<ref name=Den22211/>) of the [[Kholodny Yar]] Ukrainian [[Partisan (military)|partisan]] movement during the [[Ukrainian War of Independence]].<ref name=G121214/> In current [[Chyhyryn Raion]] this movement formed the [[Kholodny Yar Republic]] that lasted from 1919 to 1922 were they fought for Ukrainian independence and against the [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.ukrinform.ua/rubric-society/2104087-irina-gerasenko-proponue-stvoriti-nacionalnij-park-holodnij-ar.html Gerashchenko offers a National Park \"Cold Yar\"], [[Ukrinform]] (19 October 2016)</ref> The republic included 25 villages (with Melnyky serving as its \u201ccapital\u201d<ref name=Den22211/>) and could raise an army of 16 thousand.<ref name=KRbt20s/> It was the last territory held by supporters of an independent Ukrainian state before the incorporating of Ukraine into the Soviet Union as the [[Ukrainian SSR]].<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://gazeta.ua/articles/ukraine-newspaper/_na-vshanuvanni-otamana-osvyachuvali-nozhi/336125?mobile=true In honor of the chieftain blessed knives], [[Gazeta.ua]] (21 April 2010)</ref>\n\nChuchupak shot and killed himself on 12 April 1920 in fight with squadron of [[red cossacks]].<ref name=VCUinfld/><ref name=KRbt20s>{{in lang|uk}} [http://gazeta.ua/articles/cherkasy-newspaper/_na-mogilu-otamana-cuchupaki-priyihali-dvi-tisyachi-lyudej/289494 At the grave chieftain Chuchupaky came two thousand people], [[Gazeta.ua]] (16 April 2009)</ref>\n\nIn the [[21st century]] the Kholodny Republic flag was used during the [[Euromaidan]] demonstrations and by the [[Azov Battalion]].<ref name=G121214/> In January 2018 the [[93rd Mechanized Brigade (Ukraine)|93rd Mechanized Brigade]] of the [[Ukrainian army]] received the honorary name \"Kholodny Yar\" as reference to the Kholodny Yar partisan movement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukrmilitary.com/2018/01/honory-names-of-93rd-brigade.html |title=93-\u044f \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u0456\u043c'\u044f \u00ab\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u00bb |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=www.ukrmilitary.com/ |publisher=[[Ukrainian Military Pages]] |accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://procherk.info/news/7-cherkassy/59835-93-a-okrema-mehanizovana-brigada-zsu-otrimae-pochesne-najmenuvannja-holodnij-jar |title=93-\u0442\u044f \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u00ab\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u00bb |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=procherk.info/ |publisher=[[\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a (\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f)|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mil.in.ua/holodnyy-yar-pochesna-nazva-93-bryhady/ |title=\u201c\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\u201d: \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430 93 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0438 |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=mil.in.ua |publisher=[[\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0456\u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tsn.ua/ukrayina/93-a-brigada-zsu-otrimaye-pochesne-naymenuvannya-holodniy-yar-novi-shevroni-ta-boyoviy-prapor-1092280.html?g=article&m=400342745 |title=93-\u0442\u044f \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0454 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \"\u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u042f\u0440\", \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0456 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043e |author= |date=2018-01-22 |website=tsn.ua/ |publisher=[[\u0422\u0421\u041d]] |accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://milnavigator.com.ua/93-\u043e\u043c\u0431\u0440-\u0437\u0441\u0443-\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435-\u0445\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e-\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e/ 93 \u041e\u041c\u0411\u0440 \u0417\u0421\u0423 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u044e. \u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e] // ''[[\u0412\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0456\u0433\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-41973466 |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0456\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0456 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0430\u043a: \u044f\u043a \u0437\u043c\u0456\u043d\u044e\u044e\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |author= |date=2017-11-14 |website=www.bbc.com/ |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://novynarnia.com/2017/10/15/pochesni-styagi-poruch-z-boyovimi-sso-i-brigada-korolya-danila-otrimali-brendovu-simvoliku/ |title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0456 \u0441\u0442\u044f\u0433\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0447 \u0437 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c\u0438. \u0421\u0421\u041e \u0456 \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044f \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u201c\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0443\u201d \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0443 |author= |date=2017-10-15 |website=novynarnia.com|publisher=[[\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043d\u044f]] |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.slavaukraini.org/index.php?id=5#c7 www.slavaukraini.org]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140808074851/http://ukrgazeta.plus.org.ua/article.php?ida=2219 \u0413\u0415\u0420\u041e\u0407 \u00ab\u0425\u041e\u041b\u041e\u0414\u041d\u041e\u042f\u0420\u0421\u042c\u041a\u041e\u0407 \u0414\u0415\u0420\u0416\u0410\u0412\u0418\u00bb] on ukrgazeta\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chuchupak, Vasyl Stepanovych}}\n\n{{ua-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1920 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chyhyryn Raion]]\n[[Category:Peop